2026-06-13 | Count Binary Sequences of Length 2N With Equal Half Sums

	Question
Return the count modulo 10^9+7.
	Key Insight
Suppose both halves contain exactly k ones.
Number of ways to choose k ones in first half:
		C(n, k)
Number of ways to choose k ones in second half:
		C(n, k)
Therefore for a fixed k:
		ways =
		C(n,k) × C(n,k)
Summing over all possible k:
		Σ C(n,k)^2
	for k = 0 to n
A famous combinatorial identity states:
		Σ C(n,k)^2
		=
		C(2n,n)
So the answer becomes:
		C(2n,n)
	Approach
1.	Compute:
		C(2n,n)
2.	Use modular arithmetic.
3.	Precompute factorials and inverse factorials.
4.	Return result modulo 10^9+7.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    static const long long MOD = 1000000007;
    long long power(long long a, long long b) {
        long long res = 1;
        while(b) {
            if(b & 1)
                res = (res * a) % MOD;
            a = (a * a) % MOD;
            b >>= 1;
        }
        return res;
    }
    long long countBinarySeq(int n) {
        vector<long long> fact(2 * n + 1);
        vector<long long> invFact(2 * n + 1);
        fact[0] = 1;
        for(int i = 1; i <= 2 * n; i++) {
            fact[i] = (fact[i - 1] * i) % MOD;
        }
        invFact[2 * n] =
            power(fact[2 * n], MOD - 2);
        for(int i = 2 * n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            invFact[i] =
                (invFact[i + 1] * (i + 1)) % MOD;
        }
        long long ans = fact[2 * n];
        ans = (ans * invFact[n]) % MOD;
        ans = (ans * invFact[n]) % MOD;
        return ans;
    }
};
	Key Insight
Let both halves contain exactly k ones.
		First half:
		C(n,k) ways
		Second half:
		C(n,k) ways
So:
		Answer =
		Σ C(n,k)²
A well-known combinatorial identity simplifies this to:
		C(2n,n)
which is called the Central Binomial Coefficient.
